By the recent invasion, the Greeks were awakened from a dream of nine centuries 3 from the vain presumption that the capital of the Roman empire was impregnable to foreign arms. The strangers of the West had violated the city, and bestowed the sceptre, of Con- stantine: their Imperial clients soon became as unpopular as them- selves : the well-known vices of Isaac were rendered still more con- temptible by his infirmities3 and the young Alexius was hated as an apostate who had renounced the manners and religion of his country.
